Medical Report 

Patient: Mr. Guido Köhler, born on January 15, 1964, residing at Lindenstraße 27, 13156 
Berlin, patient number 542876, was treated for an exacerbated chronic obstructive 
pulmonary disease (COPD) of type GOLD B. 

History:  
Mr. Köhler, a long-time smoker, reported an increase in dyspnea and coughing with 
increased sputum production in recent days. These symptoms worsened despite the regular 
use of inhalative bronchodilators. 

Findings:  
Physical examination showed increased breathlessness on exertion and prolonged 
exhalation. Lung function tests confirmed a reduced FEV1 (Forced Expiratory Volume in one 
second), which was below 80% of the expected value, but better than 50% of the expected 
value, indicating moderate to severe COPD. 

Diagnosis:  
Exacerbated COPD GOLD B. 

Treatment:  
Medicinal treatment was intensified by introducing a combination therapy of inhaled 
corticosteroids and long-acting beta-2 agonists. Additionally, a short-term therapy with oral 
corticosteroids was started to reduce acute inflammation. Oxygen therapy was 
recommended to facilitate breathing. 

Follow-up:  
Regular follow-up appointments were scheduled to evaluate the effectiveness of the 
adjusted therapy and continue monitoring lung function. An extension of therapy might be 
necessary if symptoms persist. 

Recommendations:  
Mr. Köhler is strongly advised to immediately cease smoking to avoid further damage to the 
airways. Pulmonary rehabilitation is also recommended to improve breathing technique and 
enhance overall quality of life. 

Kind regards,
